entry.content:
The restore permission state represents whether a given origin

is eligible to show the FSA Persistent Permissions restore prompt

to the user, as per criteria defined by the FSA Persistent Permissions

feature design and Permission Decision Autoblocker criteria.

Permission Decision Autoblocker, as a result of either ignoring or

denying the restore prompt.

The cause of the problem is this call https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/touch_to_fill/password_generation/android/touch_to_fill_password_generation_controller.cc;l=103?q=touch_to_fill_password_generation_con&ss=chromium%2Fchromium%2Fsrc. With that call the button is added to the KA button bar and never removed after that.

The solution is to remove the call and stick to the logic we used to have before and allow the PasswordGenerationController to remove the button here https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/password_manager/android/password_generation_controller_impl.cc;l=362;bpv=0;bpt=1?q=password_generation_controller_imp&ss=chromium%2Fchromium%2Fsrc.

The code, which triggers the keyboard to show up is also removed for 2

reasons:

1. To not show the keyboard without the KA; the user should be able to

see their password suggestions.

2. As part of 1498350 bug fix.

entry.title: [android][listmenu] 2/n - Refactor BasicListMenu & list_menu_item.xml
entry.content:
for ui/android Migration



BasicListMenu & list_menu_item.xml are going to be migrated to

ui/android in order for WebView to leverage them and other listmenu

components. However, in order to do that the following changes were

needed:



1. The content view layout of the `BasicListMenu` has been abstracted.

The current one, app_menu_layout.xml, uses app_menu_bg.xml which

contains a custom drawable (`SurfaceColorDrawable`) that is not

compatible with WebView.



2. All list_menu_item.xml styling that is not compatible with WebView

has also been abstracted.



(Both 1 & 2 have been accomplished via. utility methods added to

`BrowserUiListMenuUtils`.)



3. list_menu_item.xml uses `?attr/selectableItemBackground` which is

not available for use in ui/android. Therefore this has been changed

to use the framework version `?android:attr/selectableItemBackground`.

The "text appearance" styling has also been abstracted (see 2).



4. `TabGridDialogMenuCoordinator` uses `list_menu_item.xml` and

previously had its own binder and properties. However

`list_menu_item.xml` already has a binder (`ListMenuItemViewBinder`) &

properties (`ListMenuItemProperties`) so `TabGridDialogMenuCoordinator`

has been updated to use them instead.

entry.title: Make the SelectorFilter stack a bit more consistent.
entry.content:
Require that we never get into a situation with inconsistent

SelectorFilter parent stacks during traversal; we now explicitly

DCHECK for that instead of just pausing traversal. This also

means we need to be slightly more lenient; whereas we'd previously

accept only the flat-tree parent, we'll now also accept

the slightly more efficient (and still correct) ParentOrShadowHost().

(The flat-tree parent is used because that's the traversal order,

but it will have a few false positives in the Bloom filter.)



Unfortunately, we can still _start_ the ElementRuleCollector in an

inconsistent state; for instance, when calculating style for

pseudo-elements, when calculating style for SVG elements,

or (I think) in some shadow-root cases. Thus, we still need to

maintain the parent stack for the sole purpose of testing

can_use_fast_reject_ at the start of the traversal. We fix a few

cases related to invalidation and shadow DOM, making invalidating

those elements marginally faster.

entry.title: [LCPP] preloading LCP candidate images with loading=lazy
entry.content:
This CL implements the preloading behavior to LCP candidate images,

which have loading="lazy" attributes behind the flag.



In theory loading="lazy" is added to the image located below the fold

for the loading start timing optimization. If the LCP image has the

attribute, that would negatively affect the metric.



This CL updates the preload scanner to create a preload request

regardless of whether the loading="lazy" attribute exists or not when

the image element is in the LCPP element locator.



In the future, we have an idea that extending this behavior to the JS

based custom lazy loading, but this CL starts from the native lazy

loading.

entry.title: Reland "WebApps: Change default for preinstalled D/S/S/D to standalone tabbed apps"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit b7c7cb59be59fafb035f62566170cbc0b663a07b



The original CL was reverted because

PreinstalledWebAppWindowExperimentBrowserTestWindow started failing.

These tests only run on official builds and wasn't caught by the CQ.

These tests depend on the default display mode of D/S/S/D and broke

with the change in expectations.



Instead of rebaselining these test expectations this CL disables the

tests entirely because the experiment they're testing has completed

and the code is now due for removal, see crbug.com/1499749.



See diff: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5004328/1..5



Original change's description:

> WebApps: Change default for preinstalled D/S/S/D to standalone tabbed apps

>

> Previously when Google Docs, Sheets, Slides, and Drive were

> preinstalled, they were set to open in a browser tab. Now that tabbed

> web apps are launched, D/S/S/D are moving to use a tabbed web app when

> installed. This CL updates the default to match (otherwise the

> DisplayMode will change on app update later).

>

> Excludes managed devices/profiles from the change to reduce disruption

> in enterprise environments. Will do a follow-up CL with some tests for

> the managed device detection.

>

> Doesn't currently set a home/new tab configuration, so tabbed editors

> will not have a home tab, and use the start_url for new tabs. Will

> follow up with a fix for that.

entry.title: Fix UploadHandler test for reauth required
entry.content:
Reading task_result.value when it has not been logged caused an MSAN

failure. We don't log TaskResult from UploaderHandler tests because

this is not done in the UploadHandler class, but by the caller.



CloudOpenMetrics needs to be able to handle this, so check if the

value has been logged before accessing it.
